  <h1>What to Do After a Civil Rights Violation</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>The period immediately after a civil rights violation is critical for preserving your legal rights. Unlike employment discrimination claims that require administrative agency filing before you can sue, &sect; 1983 claims against individual officers can generally be brought directly in federal court without prior agency exhaustion. But two urgency points dominate: many states impose notice-of-claim filing requirements with deadlines as short as 90 days before you can sue a government entity, and documentary evidence — body camera footage, surveillance recordings, incident reports — may be deleted under routine retention policies within weeks of the incident. This guide covers the specific steps to take, roughly in the order they should be taken.</p>

  <h2>Step 1: Document immediately and thoroughly</h2>
  <p>Write a detailed account of what happened as soon as possible after the incident. Your recollection of specific details will fade over days and weeks; contemporaneous accounts carry far more evidentiary weight than reconstructed narratives created months later when litigation is already underway. Document: the exact date, time, and location; the identity of every officer or official involved (badge numbers, name badges, vehicle numbers, department affiliation); the specific sequence of events leading up to and following the constitutional violation; exactly what was said by each participant; what orders were given and how you responded; who was present as witnesses; and the nature and extent of any injuries you sustained.</p>
  <p>If you were physically injured: photograph your injuries immediately and continue photographing as they develop and heal. Bruising often becomes more visible 24&ndash;48 hours after the incident. Medical records establishing the existence and extent of your injuries will be central evidence in your case; gaps in treatment create openings for defendants to minimize the severity of harm.</p>
  <p>Note details about the officers involved that will be needed to identify them in discovery: physical descriptions, any visible identifiers, patrol car numbers, radio call signs if you heard them. Officers who conceal their identity during incidents with the public may be the subject of subsequent identification disputes.</p>

  <h2>Step 2: Seek immediate medical attention</h2>
  <p>If you were physically injured, seek medical treatment promptly. Emergency room and urgent care records are among the most important pieces of evidence in a physical injury civil rights case: they are contemporaneous, they come from credentialed medical professionals, and they cannot easily be characterized as exaggeration created after litigation began. If you were taken to a hospital under arrest, request copies of all records from that visit. If you sought treatment on your own, keep all records, receipts, and notes from follow-up appointments.</p>
  <p>Medical records serve two functions in &sect; 1983 litigation: they establish the fact and extent of physical injury for compensatory damages purposes, and they can establish causation — that the injuries you sustained resulted from the constitutional violation rather than pre-existing conditions or unrelated causes. Defendants routinely argue that injuries were pre-existing; contemporaneous records documenting the sudden onset of new injuries undermine that argument.</p>

  <h2>Step 3: Preserve and request evidence immediately</h2>
  <p>Law enforcement agencies have limited retention periods for body camera footage, dashcam recordings, and surveillance video — often 30 to 90 days in many jurisdictions, sometimes less. This evidence can be destroyed under standard retention policies if you do not act quickly to request its preservation.</p>
  <p>Send written preservation demands immediately to the relevant law enforcement agency requesting that all body camera footage, dashcam video, CAD records, radio communications, and incident reports related to the incident be preserved and not destroyed. State that you anticipate litigation. An attorney can send this on your behalf with legal authority, but you can send a preservation letter yourself if you don&rsquo;t yet have counsel — the goal is to establish that the agency had notice before any routine destruction. If the agency destroys evidence after receiving a preservation demand, this can be used as spoliation evidence at trial.</p>
  <p>Request body camera footage and incident reports through your state&rsquo;s public records law or through a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request. Many civil rights attorneys will handle these requests as part of case intake.</p>
  <p>If the incident was recorded by bystanders, request copies of their recordings before they lose or delete them. If there were surveillance cameras in the area — from nearby businesses, traffic cameras, ATMs — notify your attorney so they can issue preservation letters or subpoenas before footage is automatically overwritten.</p>

  <h2>Step 4: Identify and preserve witness information</h2>
  <p>Witnesses who observed the incident can provide crucial corroboration for your account. In the immediate aftermath of a civil rights incident, identify anyone who witnessed the events: bystanders who were present, other people who were arrested at the same time, people who heard or saw what happened from nearby locations. Collect contact information — names, phone numbers, email addresses — before the scene disperses. Witnesses&rsquo; memories fade too; a brief contemporaneous statement from a witness captured shortly after the incident is more valuable than testimony reconstructed a year later.</p>
  <p>Note the demographics and approximate ages of any comparator witnesses — people who were present in circumstances similar to yours but were treated differently. Comparative evidence is central to equal protection and selective enforcement claims, and establishing who else was present and how they were treated requires knowing who those people are before they disperse and become unidentifiable.</p>

  <h2>Step 5: Satisfy state notice-of-claim requirements</h2>
  <p>This step is critical and frequently missed: many states require that anyone intending to sue a government entity file a formal notice of claim within a short period after the incident &mdash; often 90 to 180 days. This requirement is separate from and far shorter than the applicable statute of limitations. Missing a notice-of-claim deadline can bar your case against the municipality even if you file within the limitations period.</p>
  <p>States with notice-of-claim requirements include New York (90 days for claims against local government under General Municipal Law &sect; 50-e), California (six months for claims against public entities under the Government Claims Act), New Jersey (90 days), Illinois (one year), and many others. The requirement applies to claims against government entities — it does not apply (or may not apply) to individual officer claims in some states. Requirements vary by state and entity type; an attorney familiar with your state&rsquo;s law must verify the applicable deadline for your specific claim.</p>
  <p>The practical implication: consulting an attorney within the first few weeks after a civil rights incident — not after the limitations period approaches — is essential to avoid missing notice-of-claim deadlines that would bar recovery against the municipality.</p>

  <h2>Step 6: No administrative exhaustion required for most &sect; 1983 claims</h2>
  <p>Unlike employment discrimination claims under Title VII or the ADEA (which require EEOC charge filing before you can sue), &sect; 1983 civil rights claims generally do not require filing a complaint with any administrative agency before bringing a lawsuit. You may file a &sect; 1983 action in federal court directly, subject to the notice-of-claim requirements described above for municipal defendants.</p>
  <p>One exception: incarcerated plaintiffs must exhaust available administrative remedies (typically the prison grievance process) before filing a &sect; 1983 lawsuit about prison conditions under the Prison Litigation Reform Act (42 U.S.C. &sect; 1997e). For non-incarcerated plaintiffs pursuing claims arising from police conduct or other non-prison constitutional violations, no administrative exhaustion is generally required.</p>

  <h2>Step 7: Consult a civil rights attorney promptly</h2>
  <p>Section 1983 litigation is technically demanding: qualified immunity doctrine, Monell requirements for municipal claims, circuit-specific case law on what rights are &ldquo;clearly established,&rdquo; and state notice-of-claim requirements all require experienced navigation. An experienced civil rights attorney adds value at every stage: evaluating the strength of your claim, identifying the applicable notice-of-claim deadlines, managing evidence preservation, and assessing whether to file suit or pursue a settlement.</p>
  <p>Finding an attorney: most civil rights attorneys who handle &sect; 1983 cases work on contingency — they receive a percentage of any recovery, making representation accessible regardless of financial situation. The &sect; 1988 attorney fee provision also compensates attorneys for successful cases on top of any contingency arrangement. State and local bar associations, the National Police Accountability Project (NPAP), and the American Civil Liberties Union can help identify qualified civil rights attorneys in your area. Most offer free initial consultations.</p>
  <p>Timing: consult an attorney as soon as possible — not after notice-of-claim deadlines have passed and not after your memories have faded. The quality of an attorney&rsquo;s initial case assessment depends heavily on the quality of the evidence and documentation available. The earlier you consult, the more options you and your attorney will have.</p>

